alternatives.transcript: today mister palmer is a sixty two year old man who presents to the office for the chief complaint of dyspnea with exertion and fatigue mister palmer is an elementary school teacher with a wife of thirty years he was in his usual state of excellent health until week two weeks ago prior to admission when he developed an acute onset of shortness of breath he reports walking with his coworkers after work when he felt the symptoms before admission he describes the symptoms to be generalized throughout his body with a constant duration during exertion exercise seems to make it worse he does not complain of any radiating pain he rates his pain as a five out of six on a scale of zero to ten mister palmer has a history of high blood pressure which he was diagnosed with hypertension and is currently being treated for this with lisinopril ten milligrams along with the lisinopril he does not report any over the counter herbal medications mister palmer does not report any allergies his social history includes a balanced diet regular exercise before onset before the onset of symptoms two weeks ago no drug use no tobacco use no alcohol use and regular regular caffeine consumption of one and a half cups of coffee every morning he works as an elementary school teacher and is sexually active with his wife he has a positive surgical history of a cardiac cath performed one year ago at his yearly physical he's had no hospitalizations family history is positive for his pa father passing away at age fifty nine from an mi and his mother passing away at age forty from a sudden cardiac death today mister palmer appears awake alert oriented and presents with no fatigue fever chills weight loss or weight gain review of symptoms of his skin was negative with no rash bruisings lesions or color changes or warmth touch review of systems of his msk was negative no muscle back or joint pain review of pulmonary systems was positive for wheezing and dyspnea with exertion review of cardiovascular systems was positive for palpitations near syncope but no passing out no no full syncope and s four murmur and a laterally displaced pmi his vital signs seemed abnormal with an elevated bp of one thirty over ninety other vital signs were normal with a bpm of one ten and oxygen saturation of ninety six percent no carotid and brulee or jvd were noted no chest wall tenderness auscultation and palpate palpation of the epigastric area was a negative for no bruy or pulsatile mass lower extremity pulses were normal bilaterally lungs were clear to auscultation bilaterally hohmann's sign was negative and calves were symmetrical omm examination of the thoracic spine was normal no with known tar with no notable tart changes upon palpation no lower no lower extremity edema was noted review of labs ordered by the familymed physician three days ago showed cardiomegaly on chest x-ray troponin and bnp were within normal limits and a two d echo performed showed an asymmetrical left ventricle with a enlarged enlarged interventricular septum and an ejection fraction of sixty percent today mister palmer was diagnosed with familial hypertrophic obstructive cardiomyopathy and is in serious condition i counseled mister palmer to be admitted to telemetry and to check vitals q two hours he was counseled for activity as tolerated and a regular diet lisinopril ten milligrams was discontinued and disopiramide one hundred milligrams qid was instead started referrals to interventional cardiology for aicd placement and cardiothoracic surgery for possible septal myomectomy and alcohol injection were counseled thank you
